<span id="ii.xiii-p72"></span> After the description of the ant, [Prov.
vi. 6-8](../../../bib/kjv/pro006.htm#006.md)<span
id="ii.xiii-p72.1"></span>, there follows in the Septuagint a similar
reference to the bee:  “Or go to the bee, and learn how industrious she
is, and how comely she makes her work, and the produce of her labours
kings and commons adopt for health, and she is desired and esteemed by
all, and though feeble in strength has been exalted by her regard for
wisdom.”  The interpolation is supposed to be of Greek origin, as
containing “idiomatic Greek expressions which would not occur to a
translator from the Hebrew” (Delitzsch).

